 -- Function: mod_to_mermaid (M, OP_POINT, OVERRIDE_PARAMS)
     Thin wrappers over ‘mod_dataflow’ that pin the format.  Return the
     diagram source as a Maxima string, suitable for embedding in
     markdown / piping into an external renderer.


File: mochi.info,  Node: Function mod_diagram m op_point [opts],  Prev: Function mod_to_mermaid m op_point override_params,  Up: Definitions for mochi

 -- Function: mod_diagram (M, OP_POINT, [OPTS])
     One-shot front-end: build a diagram of the model and render it
     inline.  Shells out to the chosen renderer to write an SVG into
     Maxima's temp directory and prints the path so the maxima-extension
     / Aximar notebook UI picks it up and embeds the SVG content as
     ‘image/svg+xml’ in the cell output (the notebook is self-contained
     -- the temp file is read once at evaluation time and is no longer
     needed).

     Returns the SVG file path as a string.

     ‘opts’ is an optional list of equations:

        • ‘diagram’ -- only ‘'dataflow’ is supported right now
          (default).
        • ‘renderer’ -- ‘'dot’ (GraphViz, default) or ‘'mermaid’
          (Mermaid CLI). ‘'graphviz’ is accepted as an alias for ‘'dot’.
        • ‘threshold’, ‘params’ -- passed through to ‘mod_dataflow’ /
          ‘mod_state_space’.

     Renderer prerequisites:

        • ‘'dot’ -- GraphViz ‘dot’ on ‘$PATH’ (or set the ‘DOT_BIN’
          environment variable).  ‘brew install graphviz’ on macOS.
        • ‘'mermaid’ -- Mermaid CLI ‘mmdc’ on ‘$PATH’ (or set
          ‘MMDC_BIN’): ‘npm install -g @mermaid-js/mermaid-cli’.  The
          CLI itself depends on a headless Chrome via puppeteer.


